external_knowledge:
- "cinematic treasures" refers to highly regarded or popular movies;
- "attracted the most curious eyes" means movies with the highest number of accesses or views;
- "number of gazes" refers to the count of access events;
- "sparkle the brightest" refers to the top-ranking movies based on their popularity.

sql:
SELECT actor_name
FROM cast
WHERE (strftime('%Y', 'now') - strftime('%Y', birth_date)) > 50;

SELECT channel_name, COUNT(*) as channel_count 
FROM distribution_channels 
GROUP BY channel_name;

SELECT title, rating
FROM movies
WHERE rating > (SELECT AVG(rating) FROM movies);

external_knowledge:
Highly-rated movies: movies with a rating greater than 7.0;
Popularity: refers to the movie rating in this context;
One-genre wonders: movies with only one genre associated with them;

- 'Critically acclaimed films' refers to movies with an average rating greater than 7.5; 
- 'Early 21st century' refers to the time period between 2000 and 2010; 
- 'Praise from reviewers' indicates a high average rating.

sql:
SELECT m.title, m.revenue
FROM movies m
ORDER BY m.revenue DESC;

external_knowledge:
- "cast the widest cinematic shadow" is a metaphor for having the highest number of movies;
- "genres that have cast the widest cinematic shadow" refers to the genres with the highest movie counts;
- "how many films each genre has spawned" means the number of movies each genre has.

sql:
SELECT SUM(revenue) AS TotalRevenue
FROM movies
WHERE production_countries LIKE '%USA%';
